How closely do you
guys work together

00:20:12.518 --> 00:20:14.060
even though you're
on separate games?

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:15.977
Like, how closely do
"Covet" and "Design Home"

00:20:15.977 --> 00:20:18.890
work together, learn from each
other, lend each other money?

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:20.765
SARAH FUCHS: I'll start,
and you fin-- oh, we

00:20:20.765 --> 00:20:22.190
lend each other money.

00:20:22.190 --> 00:20:26.070
You know, I've only been with
Crowdstar for almost a year.

00:20:26.070 --> 00:20:29.750
And I look to Chris and
the "Design Home" team

00:20:29.750 --> 00:20:32.100
for advice and
feedback all the time.

00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:34.700
I think that "Covet's"
a five-year-old product.

00:20:34.700 --> 00:20:36.320
So "Design Home"
was really built

00:20:36.320 --> 00:20:38.875
on the back of what
"Covet" was and took

00:20:38.875 --> 00:20:40.250
a lot of great
learnings from it.

00:20:40.250 --> 00:20:42.500
But the teams work
together all the time.

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:45.110
We have the "Design
Home" content team

00:20:45.110 --> 00:20:47.668
and the "Covet" content
team working together,

00:20:47.668 --> 00:20:48.710
learning from each other.

00:20:48.710 --> 00:20:51.242
So I think we really rely
heavily on each other.

00:20:51.242 --> 00:20:53.450
We have Judy out there,
who's our director of product

00:20:53.450 --> 00:20:55.460
management, who works
for "Design Home,"

00:20:55.460 --> 00:20:57.410
but who I talk to
all the time, and who

00:20:57.410 --> 00:21:00.522
offers amazing,
relevant, helpful advice.

00:21:00.522 --> 00:21:02.480
CHRIS MCGILL: Yeah, and
the truth is I actually

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:04.020
started on "Covet Fashion."

00:21:04.020 --> 00:21:05.730
I ran BD in "Covet Fashion."

00:21:05.730 --> 00:21:06.832
I hadn't been in games.

00:21:06.832 --> 00:21:08.540
It was like drinking
through a fire hose,

00:21:08.540 --> 00:21:10.880
definitely changed the
way I looked at the world.

00:21:10.880 --> 00:21:12.770
But you know, "Fashion"
is our mother.

00:21:12.770 --> 00:21:15.610
We are built on her shoulders.

00:21:15.610 --> 00:21:19.700
You know, she fed us while
we developed the game.

00:21:19.700 --> 00:21:21.542
We took everything
that we liked about it,

00:21:21.542 --> 00:21:23.000
and we obviously
took our own take.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.030
We have a different
kind of economy.

00:21:26.030 --> 00:21:29.700
But the two games are
totally intertwined.

00:21:29.700 --> 00:21:34.310
And we like each.

00:21:34.310 --> 00:21:36.520
We like having brown
bag lunches and talking

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:39.180
about what's working,
what's not working, and why,

00:21:39.180 --> 00:21:41.922
and lending resources
when we need to.

00:21:41.922 --> 00:21:44.380
SARAH FUCHS: I think that's
one important thing about this.

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:46.820
I've been working in
games for 19 years.

00:21:46.820 --> 00:21:49.310
And Crowdstar is one of
the first places I've ever

00:21:49.310 --> 00:21:53.540
truly felt completely
supported, like with

00:21:53.540 --> 00:21:56.265
an absolute family-like
environment where you can say,

00:21:56.265 --> 00:21:58.640
hey, this is what I want to
do, and you're not running it

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:00.530
up the chain 150 times.

00:22:00.530 --> 00:22:02.610
You're actually just
like, OK, we trust you.

00:22:02.610 --> 00:22:03.340
We believe you.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:04.250
Go for it.

00:22:04.250 --> 00:22:07.372
But the Crowdstar
feeling is very familial.

00:22:07.372 --> 00:22:08.580
We really support each other.

00:22:08.580 --> 00:22:10.040
We really care about each other.

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:12.392
And you know, I'm all about
"Design Home's" success.

00:22:12.392 --> 00:22:14.850
CHRIS MCGILL: It's not like we
don't have family squabbles.

00:22:14.850 --> 00:22:17.600
SARAH FUCHS: Oh, we do,
no question about that.

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:20.683
But I think it speaks
to what the game is

00:22:20.683 --> 00:22:22.100
when you have a
team that's really

00:22:22.100 --> 00:22:23.143
supportive of each other.

00:22:23.143 --> 00:22:24.810
EMILY PUTZE: Yeah, I
think that's right.

00:22:24.810 --> 00:22:26.602
And you have different
experience sets too.

00:22:26.602 --> 00:22:29.570
I mean, Sarah, I am interested
in learning a little bit more--

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:31.375
because of your
background in gaming,

00:22:31.375 --> 00:22:33.500
you've mentioned that you
had to have this big mind

00:22:33.500 --> 00:22:37.963
shift when you came to "Covet."

00:22:37.963 --> 00:22:40.130
One of the first times I
met Chris, I said you know,

00:22:40.130 --> 00:22:41.630
it would be so great--
because I'm obviously

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:43.380
coming from a
gaming perspective--

00:22:43.380 --> 00:22:45.650
if there were timers, or
there was some gotcha,

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:46.790
or add this and this.

00:22:46.790 --> 00:22:47.332
And he said--

00:22:47.332 --> 00:22:48.665
CHRIS MCGILL: Over my dead body.

00:22:48.665 --> 00:22:50.990
EMILY PUTZE: --no, no,
no, no, that's not for us.

00:22:50.990 --> 00:22:53.780
And so how drastic was
that mind shift for you

00:22:53.780 --> 00:22:55.220
coming from the gaming world?

00:22:55.220 --> 00:22:56.630
SARAH FUCHS: Extremely drastic.

00:22:56.630 --> 00:22:59.870
I mean, gotcha, and timers,
and things like that work.

00:22:59.870 --> 00:23:00.810
They make money.

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:02.240
They make revenue.

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:06.590
And I come from mobile gaming
when it was in its infancy.

00:23:06.590 --> 00:23:08.090
And those are the
things that work.

00:23:08.090 --> 00:23:10.040
But we have a different
kind of audience.

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:11.420
We have a different
kind of game.

00:23:11.420 --> 00:23:14.150
We're really toeing the
line between game and app.

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:17.073
And it's important for us--
and it was a shock for me.

00:23:17.073 --> 00:23:18.740
It was like, OK, I
have to unlearn this.

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:20.900
I came in bubbling
with all these ideas.

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:21.830
And Chris and I--

00:23:21.830 --> 00:23:23.210
in one of our first
meetings, I was like, Chris,

00:23:23.210 --> 00:23:24.752
we could do this,
and this, and this.

00:23:24.752 --> 00:23:27.090
And he was like,
slow down there.

00:23:27.090 --> 00:23:28.070
Hang on.

00:23:28.070 --> 00:23:29.090
Your ideas are great.

00:23:29.090 --> 00:23:32.270
And we're not
going to do gotcha.

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:35.420
But I think it's
something that--

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:36.740
it's not the only way.

00:23:36.740 --> 00:23:38.240
I think that there
are a lot of ways

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:39.753
to have a successful product.

00:23:39.753 --> 00:23:42.170
CHRIS MCGILL: It actually
speaks to a lot of our qual, OK?

00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:44.930
So we have quant
coming out of our ears.

00:23:44.930 --> 00:23:45.740
And we have--

00:23:48.335 --> 00:23:49.460
Judy's sitting right there.

00:23:49.460 --> 00:23:52.850
Judy is the smartest person
on the planet, right?

00:23:52.850 --> 00:23:55.400
And we are definitely
run by our data.

00:23:55.400 --> 00:23:57.540
There's no question about it.

00:23:57.540 --> 00:23:59.960
But what our qual said
is, what women love,

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:03.500
what our users love
about us, is that--

00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:05.750
we actually divide them into
four different-- actually

00:24:05.750 --> 00:24:08.090
in your case, six-- six
different player types

00:24:08.090 --> 00:24:09.960
and what's important to them.

00:24:09.960 --> 00:24:11.910
And you know what's
important to all of them?

00:24:11.910 --> 00:24:17.220
No stress, relaxation,
creativity, inspiration.

00:24:17.220 --> 00:24:20.610
So everything we do--
like when we say, OK,

00:24:20.610 --> 00:24:22.510
we can make a million
dollars this month--

00:24:22.510 --> 00:24:24.520
OK, well does it add stress?

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:25.880
Is it inspiring?

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:26.520
Is it creative?

00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:29.820
Because if it isn't,
it doesn't go.

00:24:29.820 --> 00:24:31.100
It just doesn't go.

00:24:31.100 --> 00:24:34.563
If it is, great, let's do it.

00:24:34.563 --> 00:24:35.730
EMILY PUTZE: That's amazing.

00:24:35.730 --> 00:24:37.740
That's really unusual to be able
to stick to your user values

00:24:37.740 --> 00:24:38.040
like that.

00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:38.325
And I--

00:24:38.325 --> 00:24:39.370
CHRIS MCGILL: Well, but it's--

00:24:39.370 --> 00:24:40.330
SARAH FUCHS: It's the
core of who we are.

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:41.663
CHRIS MCGILL: It's the business.

00:24:41.663 --> 00:24:43.620
It works for the business.

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:46.610
It's not altruism, It's
really good business.

00:24:46.610 --> 00:24:47.495
EMILY PUTZE: Yeah.

00:24:47.495 --> 00:24:48.870
One question I
wanted to ask you,

00:24:48.870 --> 00:24:50.160
because it's
something that I think

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:52.260
is interesting for the style
of games you guys make,

00:24:52.260 --> 00:24:53.968
and because my colleague
Moonlit, I know,

00:24:53.968 --> 00:24:55.380
talked about this earlier--

00:24:55.380 --> 00:24:57.797
one of the things we're seeing
in the games industry right

00:24:57.797 --> 00:25:00.203
now is an increase in
exploring subscriptions.

00:25:00.203 --> 00:25:02.370
So is subscription something
that you guys have ever

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:03.330
thought about offering?

00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:05.790
Or do you have opinions
about subscriptions

00:25:05.790 --> 00:25:07.720
in mobile games in general?

00:25:07.720 --> 00:25:09.780
SARAH FUCHS: So I can't
speak to the past, what

00:25:09.780 --> 00:25:10.770
they've thought about before.

00:25:10.770 --> 00:25:12.660
But we're definitely
thinking about subscriptions.

00:25:12.660 --> 00:25:14.493
I think that there were
a lot of great talks

00:25:14.493 --> 00:25:16.800
earlier this morning.

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:19.450
I think that we need to think
about them in a different way.

00:25:19.450 --> 00:25:21.410
We definitely are--
in fact, I have

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:23.160
a meeting about this this week.

00:25:23.160 --> 00:25:25.290
But we need to think about
how they work for "Covet

00:25:25.290 --> 00:25:26.760
Fashion" and "Design Home."

00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:28.530
Because what works
for one type of game

00:25:28.530 --> 00:25:29.970
is not necessarily
going to work.

00:25:29.970 --> 00:25:32.178
But I think subscriptions
has a ton of possibilities.

00:25:32.178 --> 00:25:34.860
I think there are ways we
could explore it, maybe,

00:25:34.860 --> 00:25:38.118
with in-real-life stuff
tied into our products.

00:25:38.118 --> 00:25:39.660
So I don't know what
that looks like.

00:25:39.660 --> 00:25:41.520
I think there's just
a great future for it.

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:43.590
CHRIS MCGILL: We were
just kibitzing over here

00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:44.730
while Moonlit was talking.

00:25:44.730 --> 00:25:46.870
We were like, OK,
maybe we need to think

00:25:46.870 --> 00:25:48.120
about this in a different way.

00:25:48.120 --> 00:25:51.540
And maybe there's something that
we, as a very different entity,

00:25:51.540 --> 00:25:55.380
can bring to the table
that takes those elements

00:25:55.380 --> 00:25:57.730
but also adds other
elements into it.

00:25:57.730 --> 00:26:00.510
And it's frightening at
first, to think about it,

00:26:00.510 --> 00:26:02.133
like ooh, I got a good business.

00:26:02.133 --> 00:26:03.300
I don't want to cannibal it.

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:04.450
And you're like
don't screw it up.

00:26:04.450 --> 00:26:05.200
Don't screw it up.

00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:06.150
Don't screw it up.

00:26:06.150 --> 00:26:08.800
But we are a company
that takes chances.

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:12.540
And I think we might talk
about a unique take on it.

00:26:12.540 --> 00:26:14.610
SARAH FUCHS: Nice use
of the word "kibitzing."

00:26:14.610 --> 00:26:16.442
That was great.

00:26:16.442 --> 00:26:18.900
EMILY PUTZE: OK, let's switch
gears and do lightning round,

00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:21.900
because I think we have
a couple minutes left.

00:26:21.900 --> 00:26:27.150
But I have some good questions
that I have stored here.

00:26:27.150 --> 00:26:29.110
So lightning round-- ready?

00:26:29.110 --> 00:26:31.380
I wish I could limit your
answers to, like, words--

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:32.640
like three words each--
to make it harder.

00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:33.090
But let's not do that.

00:26:33.090 --> 00:26:33.300
CHRIS MCGILL: Green.

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:33.870
SARAH FUCHS: Three words each

00:26:33.870 --> 00:26:35.037
EMILY PUTZE: No, no, please.

00:26:35.037 --> 00:26:36.270
SARAH FUCHS: Green.

00:26:36.270 --> 00:26:37.603
CHRIS MCGILL: I said that first.

00:26:37.603 --> 00:26:40.320
EMILY PUTZE: What year
will "Design Home"

00:26:40.320 --> 00:26:44.040
have its first AR,
integration, if ever?

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:47.993
CHRIS MCGILL: Next year,
in selective settings.

00:26:47.993 --> 00:26:48.660
EMILY PUTZE: OK.

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:53.340
How many games will
Crowdstar have live in 2021?

00:26:53.340 --> 00:26:56.130
SARAH FUCHS: More than three.

00:26:56.130 --> 00:26:58.980
EMILY PUTZE: What's one thing
you wish you knew a year ago

00:26:58.980 --> 00:27:01.490
and subsequently
did differently?

00:27:01.490 --> 00:27:02.740
CHRIS MCGILL: This one's easy.

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:07.080
I wish I'd put more energy and
more focus into recruiting.

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:10.500
Because we're growing
really quickly.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:12.705
And it's really hard
sometimes, especially when

00:27:12.705 --> 00:27:15.960
you're doing live ops, to
lay down the track right

00:27:15.960 --> 00:27:18.190
before the train goes over it.

00:27:18.190 --> 00:27:20.760
And if any Unity engineers
are in the crowd,

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:21.690
meet me at the bar.

00:27:24.250 --> 00:27:25.517
SARAH FUCHS: Analysts too.

00:27:25.517 --> 00:27:26.710
EMILY PUTZE: Analysts?

00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:28.810
CHRIS MCGILL: Just
about anybody, actually.

00:27:28.810 --> 00:27:30.442
EMILY PUTZE: Sarah,
what about you?

00:27:30.442 --> 00:27:31.900
Same question-- so
what's one thing

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:34.805
you wish you knew a year ago
that you would do differently?

00:27:34.805 --> 00:27:36.430
SARAH FUCHS: You
know, it's hard for me

00:27:36.430 --> 00:27:38.347
to say-- to have a
different answer than that.

00:27:38.347 --> 00:27:43.150
But I wish that we had done
our "Covet Fashion" personas

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:44.020
earlier.

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:47.110
So I wish that we had been
able to really deep dive

00:27:47.110 --> 00:27:50.320
on who our players are
earlier than we did.

00:27:50.320 --> 00:27:53.030
Because we're having
a record year.

00:27:53.030 --> 00:27:54.430
It's incredible.

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:56.490
And I think if we knew
then what we know now,

00:27:56.490 --> 00:27:58.990
we could have-- last year could
have been a record year too.

00:27:58.990 --> 00:28:00.820
EMILY PUTZE: Awesome.

00:28:00.820 --> 00:28:02.890
Name another game
developer that you admire.

00:28:04.995 --> 00:28:05.870
SARAH FUCHS: Network.

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:11.570
CHRIS MCGILL: I admire, I think,
Playworks for their success

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:15.620
and Roblox for their innovation.

00:28:15.620 --> 00:28:18.110
EMILY PUTZE: Have you
or anyone you know ever

00:28:18.110 --> 00:28:20.872
bought furniture out
of "Design Home?"

00:28:20.872 --> 00:28:21.580
SARAH FUCHS: Yes.

00:28:21.580 --> 00:28:24.425
CHRIS MCGILL: Yes,
including my wife.

00:28:24.425 --> 00:28:26.300
EMILY PUTZE: What about
clothes from "Covet?"

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:28.160
SARAH FUCHS: Yes,
including myself.

00:28:28.160 --> 00:28:29.303
EMILY PUTZE: All right.

00:28:29.303 --> 00:28:31.345
SARAH FUCHS: It's great
when you go into a store,

00:28:31.345 --> 00:28:33.470
and you're like,
that's our brand.

00:28:33.470 --> 00:28:34.435
And then you buy it.

00:28:34.435 --> 00:28:35.775
EMILY PUTZE: That's true.

00:28:35.775 --> 00:28:37.880
It's useful, learning,
part of the hook.

00:28:37.880 --> 00:28:39.070
SARAH FUCHS: Exactly

00:28:39.070 --> 00:28:41.060
EMILY PUTZE: OK,
parting advice--

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:43.670
Chris, if you could offer
other game developers

00:28:43.670 --> 00:28:45.800
one piece of advice
when it comes

00:28:45.800 --> 00:28:50.540
to how they approach new game
design, what would that be?

00:28:50.540 --> 00:28:52.850
CHRIS MCGILL: I think it's
write a value proposition.

00:28:52.850 --> 00:28:55.730
I think games universally
try to solve the value

00:28:55.730 --> 00:28:58.820
proposition of I'm bored.

00:28:58.820 --> 00:29:02.030
But if you can entertain
people and tie it intrinsically

00:29:02.030 --> 00:29:06.350
to their life outside the
game, that's defensible.

00:29:06.350 --> 00:29:08.040
That's totally different.

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:09.310
It's additive.

00:29:09.310 --> 00:29:10.690
It may not be curing cancer.

00:29:10.690 --> 00:29:12.680
It might not be Mother
Teresa's work, right?

00:29:12.680 --> 00:29:15.550
But it is additive, it's not
what other people are doing,

00:29:15.550 --> 00:29:19.830
and you're competing
on a different plane.

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:22.493
EMILY PUTZE: Sarah,
knowing what you know now,

00:29:22.493 --> 00:29:23.910
for game developers
who are trying

00:29:23.910 --> 00:29:26.070
to pursue more meaningful
engagement or more

00:29:26.070 --> 00:29:28.800
sustainable
monetization strategies,

00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:31.062
do you have any tactical advice?

00:29:31.062 --> 00:29:33.270
SARAH FUCHS: Create a
relationship with your players,

00:29:33.270 --> 00:29:34.687
people who actually
play the game.

00:29:34.687 --> 00:29:37.187
Think about the emotions you
want them to have while they're

00:29:37.187 --> 00:29:38.880
playing, and as Chris
said, the emotion

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:40.980
you want them to have when
they put the game down.

00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:42.960
And have that be
your North Star.

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:44.995
And focus on that
relationship with the player.

00:29:44.995 --> 00:29:46.620
CHRIS MCGILL: And
that can be measured.

00:29:46.620 --> 00:29:49.405
I mean, it can be
measured qualitatively.

00:29:49.405 --> 00:29:50.530
EMILY PUTZE: Well, awesome.

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:53.990
Thank you guys so much for
doing this with me today.

00:29:53.990 --> 00:29:56.907
I hope everyone feels like
they learned something.

00:29:56.907 --> 00:29:57.865
SARAH FUCHS: Thank you.

00:29:57.865 --> 00:29:59.657
CHRIS MCGILL: I have
one more thing to say.

00:29:59.657 --> 00:30:01.420
What I really like
about it is we're

00:30:01.420 --> 00:30:03.220
doing something very different.

00:30:03.220 --> 00:30:05.860
And it's clear to me,
Emily and Moonlit,

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:08.590
that you have gotten
what we've done.

00:30:08.590 --> 00:30:10.420
You've been a champion for this.

00:30:10.420 --> 00:30:12.318
And it's the best.

00:30:12.318 --> 00:30:14.110
EMILY PUTZE: I think
it's important to show

00:30:14.110 --> 00:30:16.600
that you can be different
and extremely successful.

00:30:16.600 --> 00:30:18.610
And so thank you so much
for joining us today.

00:30:18.610 --> 00:30:19.610
CHRIS MCGILL: Thank you.

00:30:19.610 --> 00:30:20.568
